<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-638-771  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 638 771.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>LAN Times  Nov 19 1990 v7 n14 p18(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>New fiber-optic network promises 44Mbps throughput: performancelimited only by the speed of servers. (Ancor CXT local areanetwork; Thomas-Conrad Network System) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dryden, Patrick.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Ancor Communications Inc announces the CXT fiber-optic local areanetwork (LAN), offering uniform 44Mbps performance regardless ofloading or node growth on NetWare 386 networks by theestablishment of point-to-point access through a centralhigh-speed switch.andP;  A self-configuring circuit exchange terminal(CXT) is the central hub, setting up direct, full-duplex channelsbetween nodes and completing each two-way transaction beforemoving on to the next.andP;  Each CXT chassis supports up to 64channels, in 16-port increments, and can be cascaded withouttaking a user port.andP;  Connection cost per node, before cabling, is$1,912.andP;  Initial CXT adapters are $1,090 each, and a switchingunit with one 16-channel module is $13,000.andP;  Channel upgrades alsocost $13,000.andP;  Thomas-Conrad Corp targets high-performance withits Thomas-Conrad Network System (TCNS), a token passing networkthat handles traffic at 100Mbps.andP;  Connection cost for the TCNS is$1,782, excluding cable.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Ancor Communications Inc. (Product introduction)Thomas-Conrad Corp. (Product introduction).andO;Product:   Ancor CXT (Local area network) (Product introduction)Thomas-Conrad Network System (Computer network) (Productintroduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionPerformanceLocal Area Networks.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Fiber-optic LAN. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>